definition.value: Any drug that incapacitates another person and renders them vulnerable to a sexual assault, including rape. The substances are associated with date rape because of reported incidents of their use in the context of two people dating, during which the victim is sexually assaulted or raped, or suffers other indignities. The substances are not exclusively used to perpetrate sexual assault or rape, but are the properties or side-effects of substances normally used for legitimate medical purposes. One of the most common incapacitating agents for date rape is alcohol, administered either surreptitiously or consumed voluntarily, rendering the victim unable to make informed decisions or give consent.
Any marital relationship which is strictly monogamous.
Any marital relationship which is not strictly monogamous.
Any marital relationship which is polygamous.
Any marital relationship that is bigamous.
A marital relationship in which two people marry as virgins, remain sexually exclusive their entire lives, and become celibate upon the death of their partner.
A marital relationship with only one person at a time. For instance, if a partner dies or becomes separated or divorced, another monogamous marriage may occur.
Differences in patterns of orientation for social interaction.
Romantic identity is how one thinks of oneself in terms of to whom one is romantically attracted.
A sequence of expected behaviors for a given situation.
A sequence of expected behaviors for sexual situations, often built from preconceived notions of what sexual intercourse is like (conditioned by material such as pornography).

A theory that predicts certain intergroup behaviours on the basis of perceived group status differences, the perceived legitimacy and stability of those status differences, and the perceived ability to move from one group to another.
Sexual attraction between members of the same gender.

Note that same-sex and same-gender sexual attraction are listed as synonyms in this entry. This may not always be the case depending on the type of organism (i.e. human or non-human) or when considering sex vs. gender in various arenas. In general, attraction is based on a number of factors in humans, including gender expression (but not unknowable biological factors such as chromosomal composition or individual gene expression).
Sexual attraction between members of different genders.
Hypersexual behavior observed as a symptom related to bipolar disorder.
Hypersexual behavior observed as a symptom related to depressive disorders.
Hypersexual behavior observed as a symptom related to manic behavior.
Hypersexual behavior observed as a symptom related to Parkinson's disease.
A social phenomenon that occurs when two individuals interact and one or both feel sexual desire, but the consummation is postponed or never happens.
The outward phenotype or look of an organism.
The outward phenotype or look of human beings.
A quality that causes an interest, desire in, or gravitation to something or someone.
The degree to which a person's physical features are considered aesthetically pleasing or beautiful.
An individual's ability to attract the sexual or erotic interests of other people, and is a factor in sexual selection or mate choice.
Sexual abstinence undertaken in which a person expects to have sexual intercourse or engage in sexual activities at some point in the future.
Sexual abstinence undertaken in which a person does not expect to engage in sexual intercourse or activities for the rest of their life.

The practice of refraining from sexual experiences in order to increase erotic arousal and/or tension. The prohibited experience can be narrowly or broadly defined and banned for a specific or indeterminate length of time depending on the practitioner. The experience withheld can be any favored or desired sexual activities, such as specific acts or positions, provided it is something the practitioner wants. Erotic sexual denial is commonly used as sex play between intimate partners, but it can also be indulged in as an individual practice.
Sexual denial which includes total avoidance of genital stimulation to the penis or vulva. This often involves the use of a physical barrier or device such as a chastity belt.
A situation where a person is stimulated until they are close to orgasm, then stimulation is stopped, keeping the person on the brink of orgasm.
Similar to orgasm control, but without the promise of orgasm at the end.
An artery disorder characterized by chronic elevated blood pressure in the arteries.
A vascular disorder located in an artery.
A condition involving temporary fluid congestion (vasocongestion) in the testicles accompanied by testicular pain, caused by prolonged sexual arousal in the human male without ejaculation.
Awareness about sexual assault and education about how to prevent sexual violence.
An attack, abuse, or assault committed against a person who is perceived by the aggressor to be a member of the LGBTQIA+ community.
Verbal or physical abuse against a person who is perceived by the aggressor to be a gay man, including men who are actually heterosexual.
Verbal or physical abuse against a person who is perceived by the aggressor to be a lesbian, including women who are actually heterosexual.
Verbal or physical abuse against a person who is perceived by the aggressor to be transgender, including persons who are actually cisgender.
Bullying perpetrated by a single person against a target ot targets.
Bullying perpetrated by a group against a target ot targets.
Any bullying that hurts someone's body or damages their possessions. Stealing, shoving, hitting, fighting, and intentionally destroying someone's property are types of physical bullying.
Bullying that is conducted by speaking or other use of the voice and does not involve any physical contact.

Any kind of bullying which uses relationships to hurt others; alternatively, any bullying that is done with the intent to hurt somebody's reputation or social standing which can also link in with the techniques included in physical and verbal bullying.
The use of technology to harass, threaten, embarrass, or target another person.
A type of bullying, that occurs in any educational setting.
Bullying as experienced by members of the military.
Bullying which involves some sexual- or gender-based component.

A persistent pattern of mistreatment from others in the workplace that causes either physical or emotional harm. It can include such tactics as verbal, nonverbal, psychological, physical abuse and humiliation.
A form of workplace bullying which takes places in the institutions of higher education, such as colleges and universities in a wide range of actions.
Bullying of persons with disabilities or perceived as having a disability or disabilities.
Bullying of persons in the teaching profession.
